  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When multiple agents access shared external resources \u2014 a database, a file, a cached object outside LangGraph state \u2014 concurrent writes can corrupt data. Python's asyncio library provides three core primitives: ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lock",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for exclusive access, ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "asyncio.Semaphore",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for bounded concurrency, and reader-writer patterns for workloads that are read-heavy. LangGraph's reducer annotations offer a lock-free alternative for state that lives inside the graph."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Locking and synchronization patterns: mutex, read-write lock, semaphore, and LangGraph reducers",
          "title": "Locking & Synchronization Patterns"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "asyncio.Lock \u2014 Exclusive Resource Access"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "asyncio.Lock",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " allows only one coroutine to hold it at a time. All others await until it is released. Use it when two agents must not simultaneously read-modify-write the same mutable object:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\nfrom typing import Any\n\n# Shared mutable cache outside LangGraph state\n_cache: dict[str, Any] = {}\n_cache_lock = asyncio.Lock()\n\n\nasync def cache_get(key: str) -> Any | None:\n    async with _cache_lock:  # shared read is safe without lock, but\n        return _cache.get(key)  # shown here for simplicity\n\n\nasync def cache_set(key: str, value: Any) -> None:\n    async with _cache_lock:\n        _cache[key] = value\n\n\nasync def cache_update(key: str, value: Any) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Read-modify-write: MUST hold lock for the whole operation.\"\"\"\n    async with _cache_lock:\n        existing = _cache.get(key, [])\n        _cache[key] = existing + [value]  # safe: lock held throughout"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "async with _cache_lock",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " context manager acquires on entry and releases on exit \u2014 even if an exception is raised. Never do a bare ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "await lock.acquire()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " without a matching ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "lock.release()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in a ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "finally",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " block."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using a Lock Inside a LangGraph Node"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from langgraph.graph import StateGraph, END\nfrom typing_extensions import TypedDict\nfrom typing import Annotated\nimport operator\n\n# Module-level lock \u2014 created once, shared across all node invocations\n_db_lock = asyncio.Lock()\n\n\nclass ResearchState(TypedDict):\n    results: Annotated[list[str], operator.add]\n    query: str\n\n\nasync def researcher_a(state: ResearchState) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Queries an external API; lock protects a rate-limited connection.\"\"\"\n    async with _db_lock:\n        # Only one researcher at a time touches the rate-limited client\n        result = await _rate_limited_api(state[\"query\"] + \" angle A\")\n    return {\"results\": [result]}\n\n\nasync def researcher_b(state: ResearchState) -> dict:\n    async with _db_lock:\n        result = await _rate_limited_api(state[\"query\"] + \" angle B\")\n    return {\"results\": [result]}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Declare the lock at module scope so it is shared across all invocations of nodes in the same process. If the lock is created inside the node function, each call gets a fresh lock and they never actually synchronise."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Reader-Writer Pattern"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "asyncio has no built-in reader-writer lock, but the pattern is straightforward to implement. Multiple agents can read simultaneously; a writer waits for all readers to finish, then blocks all new readers while writing:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\n\n\nclass RWLock:\n    \"\"\"Allows concurrent reads; exclusive writes.\"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self) -> None:\n        self._readers = 0\n        self._write_lock = asyncio.Lock()\n        self._read_lock = asyncio.Lock()  # protects _readers counter\n\n    async def acquire_read(self) -> None:\n        async with self._read_lock:\n            self._readers += 1\n            if self._readers == 1:         # first reader blocks writers\n                await self._write_lock.acquire()\n\n    async def release_read(self) -> None:\n        async with self._read_lock:\n            self._readers -= 1\n            if self._readers == 0:         # last reader unblocks writers\n                self._write_lock.release()\n\n    async def acquire_write(self) -> None:\n        await self._write_lock.acquire()   # waits for all readers to leave\n\n    def release_write(self) -> None:\n        self._write_lock.release()\n\n\n# Shared document store\n_documents: dict[str, str] = {}\n_rw_lock = RWLock()\n\n\nasync def read_document(doc_id: str) -> str:\n    await _rw_lock.acquire_read()\n    try:\n        return _documents.get(doc_id, \"\")\n    finally:\n        await _rw_lock.release_read()\n\n\nasync def write_document(doc_id: str, content: str) -> None:\n    await _rw_lock.acquire_write()\n    try:\n        _documents[doc_id] = content\n    finally:\n        _rw_lock.release_write()"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This implementation favours readers: a new reader can acquire even while other readers hold the lock. If your workload is write-heavy (many agents write, few read), you may need a writer-preference variant that queues new readers behind pending writers."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "asyncio.Semaphore \u2014 Bounded Concurrency"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A semaphore lets up to N coroutines proceed simultaneously. This is the right tool when you want multiple agents to work in parallel but must not saturate a downstream resource (an LLM API, a database connection pool, a third-party service):"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\nfrom langgraph.types import Send\nfrom langchain_anthropic import ChatAnthropic\nfrom typing_extensions import TypedDict\nfrom typing import Annotated\nimport operator\n\nllm = ChatAnthropic(model=\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\")\n_llm_semaphore = asyncio.Semaphore(3)  # at most 3 LLM calls in flight\n\n\nclass WorkItem:\n    def __init__(self, query: str):\n        self.query = query\n\n\nclass PipelineState(TypedDict):\n    queries: list[str]\n    answers: Annotated[list[str], operator.add]\n\n\nasync def worker(item: WorkItem) -> dict:\n    async with _llm_semaphore:\n        response = await llm.ainvoke(item.query)\n    return {\"answers\": [response.content]}\n\n\ndef dispatcher(state: PipelineState) -> list[Send]:\n    return [Send(\"worker\", WorkItem(q)) for q in state[\"queries\"]]\n\n\nfrom langgraph.graph import StateGraph, END\n\nbuilder = StateGraph(PipelineState)\nbuilder.add_node(\"worker\", worker)\nbuilder.set_entry_point(\"dispatcher\")\nbuilder.add_node(\"dispatcher\", lambda s: {})\nbuilder.add_conditional_edges(\"dispatcher\", dispatcher)\nbuilder.add_edge(\"worker\", END)\ngraph = builder.compile()"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Even if LangGraph fans out 50 workers via ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Send",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", only 3 will hold the semaphore at any moment. The others await a free slot. This provides back-pressure without requiring complex queue management."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "asyncio.Event \u2014 Signal-Based Coordination"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "asyncio.Event",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " acts as a one-shot (or resettable) gate. One agent sets it; others that are ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "await",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "ing on it are all released simultaneously. This replaces polling loops:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\n\n_data_ready = asyncio.Event()\n_shared_data: dict = {}\n\n\nasync def producer_node(state: dict) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Fetch data from an API; signal consumers when ready.\"\"\"\n    _shared_data[\"result\"] = await _fetch_external_data(state[\"url\"])\n    _data_ready.set()   # wake all waiting consumers\n    return {}\n\n\nasync def consumer_node(state: dict) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Wait until the producer signals data is available.\"\"\"\n    await _data_ready.wait()  # blocks until set() is called\n    return {\"output\": _shared_data[\"result\"]}\n\n\nasync def orchestrate() -> None:\n    \"\"\"Run producer and consumer concurrently.\"\"\"\n    producer_task = asyncio.create_task(producer_node({\"url\": \"https://example.com\"}))\n    consumer_task = asyncio.create_task(consumer_node({}))\n    await asyncio.gather(producer_task, consumer_task)\n    _data_ready.clear()  # reset for next use if orchestrate() is called again"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Unlike a lock, an event has no owner. Any coroutine can call ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "set()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " or ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "clear()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Call ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "clear()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " before the next cycle if the event needs to gate more than one round of work."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lock-Free Synchronization: LangGraph Reducers"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For state that lives inside the LangGraph ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "TypedDict",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", reducers replace locks entirely. The runtime collects all parallel node outputs and merges them after all nodes in a parallel branch finish \u2014 atomically, with no possibility of interleaving:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import operator\nfrom typing import Annotated\nfrom typing_extensions import TypedDict\nfrom langgraph.graph import StateGraph, END\nfrom langgraph.types import Send\n\n\nclass AggState(TypedDict):\n    # All parallel writes are safe \u2014 no lock needed\n    partial_scores: Annotated[list[float], operator.add]\n    errors: Annotated[list[str], operator.add]\n\n\nclass EvalTask:\n    def __init__(self, item_id: str):\n        self.item_id = item_id\n\n\ndef evaluator(task: EvalTask) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Each parallel invocation writes to its own list slice.\"\"\"\n    try:\n        score = _compute_score(task.item_id)\n        return {\"partial_scores\": [score]}\n    except Exception as exc:\n        return {\"errors\": [f\"{task.item_id}: {exc}\"]}\n\n\ndef fan_out(state: AggState) -> list[Send]:\n    items = [\"item1\", \"item2\", \"item3\", \"item4\"]\n    return [Send(\"evaluator\", EvalTask(i)) for i in items]\n\n\ndef aggregator(state: AggState) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Called after all evaluators finish; sees the merged lists.\"\"\"\n    avg = sum(state[\"partial_scores\"]) / len(state[\"partial_scores\"]) if state[\"partial_scores\"] else 0.0\n    return {\"partial_scores\": [avg]}  # replace list with single summary\n\n\nbuilder = StateGraph(AggState)\nbuilder.add_node(\"evaluator\", evaluator)\nbuilder.add_node(\"aggregator\", aggregator)\nbuilder.set_entry_point(\"fan_out_node\")\nbuilder.add_node(\"fan_out_node\", lambda s: {})\nbuilder.add_conditional_edges(\"fan_out_node\", fan_out)\nbuilder.add_edge(\"evaluator\", \"aggregator\")\nbuilder.add_edge(\"aggregator\", END)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Parallel ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "evaluator",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " nodes each return ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "{\"partial_scores\": [x]}",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". LangGraph's runtime calls ",
            "marks": []
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "operator.add",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " on all four results after they finish, producing a single flat list \u2014 no locks, no races, no asyncio primitives needed."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Avoiding Deadlocks and Lock Contention"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Deadlocks occur when two agents each hold a lock the other needs. In multi-agent systems the most common patterns are:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Lock ordering: always acquire locks in the same global order across all nodes. If agent A acquires ",
                    "marks": []
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "lock_1",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " then ",
                    "marks": []
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "lock_2",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ", every other agent must do the same. Never reverse the order."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Timeout acquisition: use ",
                    "marks": []
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "asyncio.wait_for(lock.acquire(), timeout=5.0)",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " to detect hangs. Raise an error rather than waiting indefinitely."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Minimise critical sections: do all CPU-bound preparation outside the lock. Only the shared-resource access should occur inside ",
                    "marks": []
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "async with lock",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Prefer reducers: if the data can live in LangGraph state, use a reducer instead of a lock. Reducers are guaranteed deadlock-free by the runtime."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\n\n_lock_a = asyncio.Lock()\n_lock_b = asyncio.Lock()\n\n\nasync def safe_two_lock_operation(data_a: str, data_b: str) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Always acquire in alphabetical order \u2014 never reverse.\"\"\"\n    async with _lock_a:\n        async with _lock_b:\n            await _write_both(data_a, data_b)\n\n\nasync def timed_lock_acquire(lock: asyncio.Lock, timeout: float = 5.0) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Returns False if lock could not be acquired within timeout.\"\"\"\n    try:\n        await asyncio.wait_for(lock.acquire(), timeout=timeout)\n        return True\n    except asyncio.TimeoutError:\n        return False"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Choosing the Right Primitive"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableHeader",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Primitive"
                      }
                    ]
